Orinoco was good, but other restaurants are better.  The entrance was a wrought-iron ivy gate, and passing through felt like discovering a secret world. Inside this small restaurant, the decor was thematic, and the cramped seating, though uncomfortable, fit the indie aesthetic.  I ordered the grill plate, which came with steak, chicken, and chorizo for $26. All three meats were good enough, but "good enough" doesn't deserve five stars. Especially not with such underwhelming service.  Orinoco has the misfortune of being a good restaurant surrounded by great ones. For hole-in-the-wall charm, I'd go to Pinocchio's Pizza or 9 Tastes Thai, both on the same block and at a lower price point. For great food, I'd go to Park, just across the street. Orinoco may be good, but not good enough to go back to.

Everything was delicious and pretty good portion sizes for the price in my opinion. Servers were super nice and they have inside and outdoor patio seating as well.

While their name sounds more like a gas station, this is a cool little South American eatery tucked in an alley of Harvard Square. They have a diverse menu of a variety of arepas, empanadas, pepitos (sandwiches), and principales (main dishes). Many of these menu items are very authentic South American dishes that you would be hard-pressed to find in any other restaurant. I personally would recommend sticking to the pepitos and principales, since I've found to be very wholesome and well thought-out plates. The empanadas are served with a central salad presentation and can be a bit dry and heavy. For filling a rare culinary niche in Harvard Square, I would score the place 5 stars, but it can be challenging to get seats (no reservations) and their sometimes rather brusque service detracts one star.
